<body>

#fragment/navbar.html

  <h1><a name="intro">Forms with change history</a></h1>

  <ul>
  <li><a href="bootstrap5.html">The Bootstrap5 implementation.</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>WARNING:</strong>
  This plugin is "new technology": it adds something to webforms
  which changes the way we think about forms.  Traditionally, there
  is only one kind of user data: data which matches the current form.
  This plugin changes this: the user data is in transition towards the
  expectations of the latest form.  People will need to get used to this
  extra visual help.</p>

  <h2><a name="ratio">Rationale</a></h2>

  <p>Immediately after a form gets implemented, it enters the
  "maintenance" phase: every once-in-a-while, the form needs to get
  updated.  Adding fields, removing fields, changing fields.  In common
  practice, the users of the form is not informed about those changes.
  However, that may not be the optimal experience, both from the form
  owner and from the form user's perspective.</p>

  <p>A few examples where it would really help to display the changes
  since the last visit of the user:</p>
  <ul>
  <li>the user gets a new option to indicate whether the phone number is for home or work,
  <li>the accepted length of the company description has been enlarged,
  <li>the license has to be reconfirmed,
  <li>a new gender option was added which may fit you better, or
  <li>the postal address became optional: you are allowed to remove it.
  </ul>

  <p>Over time, small changes to the form are made.  How do you
  communicate them clearly to a user?  This based on the knowledge: when
  did the user visit the form last?</p>

  <h2><a name="recording">Recording changes</a></h2>

  <p>The key idea behind this plugin, is that the form developer records
  the changes which were made to the form fields.  Based on the knowledge
  about the last visit of the user to the form page, this plugin translate
  the change records into minimal visual hints for that user.  With these
  hints, the user can better adapt the submitted data than without help.</p>

  <p>The form change record is added to the HTML in divs.  What has changed
  and when is encoded in class attributes and data attributes.  When the form
  is loaded, it is informed about the version of the form when the user clicked
  "Save" last.  All the form changes since that moment will get visualized.</p>

  <h2><a name="version">Form and data version</a></h2>

  <p>To be able to see the changes, you need to track the version of the form
  which the user filled-in.  This is not the version of the form on the moment
  the user submits, but the version the user saw in the browser.  Typically, your
  form starts like this:</p>

#fragment/form-version.html.code

  <p>The version <strong>MUST be strictly alphabetically ordered</strong>.  A date
  with or without time will do.  Versions like '<tt>2.8.12</tt>' will <em>not</em>
  work.</p>

  <p>When the server accepts the form data, it shall implement something like:

#fragment/backend-accept.perl.code

  <p>Translate this to your own server language and web-framework.  (I will include
  your solutions as examples, if you contribute them.)</p>

  <h2><a name="future">Future developments</a></h2>

  <ul>
  <li>porting the features to other web frameworks than Bootstrap5.</li>
  <li>create a better website.</li>
  </ul>

</body>
</html>
